    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="essay">
                <head><bibl><author type="writer"><name><ref target="people.html#BarbauldMrs">Anna
                                    Letitia Barbauld</ref></name></author><title type="main"
                            level="a"><ref target="people.html#HawkesworthJohn"
                                    >HAWKESWORTH</ref>.<note><title level="m"><hi
                                        rendition="#italics">The British Novelists; with an Essay;
                                        and Prefaces, Biographical and Critical, by <ref
                                            target="people.html#BarbauldMrs">Mrs.
                                        Barbauld</ref></hi></title>, 50 Vols. (London: Printed for
                                F.C. and J. Rivington; W. Otridge and Son; A. Strahan; T. Payne; G.
                                Robinson; W. Lowndes; Wilkie and Robinson; Scatcherd and Letterman;
                                J. Walker; Vernor, Hood, and Sharpe; R. Lea; J. Nunn; Lackington and
                                Co.; Clarke and Son; C. Law; Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme; Cadell
                                and Davies; E. Jeffery; J.K. Newman; Crosby and Co.; J. Carpenter;
                                S. Bagster; T. Booth; J. Murray; J. and J. Richardson; Black, Parry,
                                and Kingsbury; J. Harding; R. Phillips; J. Mawman; J. Booker; J.
                                Asperne; R. Baldwin; Mathews and Leigh; J. Faulder; Johnson and Co.;
                                Sherwood and Co.; J. Miller; W. Creech, Edinburgh; and Wilson and
                                Son, York, 1810), 26: i-ii. Victoria Wynn and Mary A. Waters
                                co-edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                                    Archive</hi>. </note></title></bibl></head>
                <p rendition="#noindent"><hi rendition="#largest">T</hi>HE praise which was
                    universally bestowed on the little Eastern tales which <ref
                        target="people.html#HawkesworthJohn">Dr. Hawkesworth</ref> had introduced in
                    the papers of his <title><hi rendition="#italics">Adventurer</hi></title>,
                    probably suggested to him the idea of giving a more extended story in the same
                    style, and produced his <title><hi rendition="#italics">Almoran and
                        Hamet</hi></title>. It is not, however, equal to the beautiful allegory of
                    the <hi rendition="#italics">ring</hi>,<note><ref
                            target="people.html#BarbauldMrs">Barbauld</ref> probably refers to a
                        story in the <title><hi rendition="#italics">Adventurer</hi></title> (No.
                        20, Saturday, January 13, 1753; continued through No. 21, Tuesday, January
                        15 and No. 22, Saturday, January 20). With <ref
                            target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Samuel Johnson</ref>, Hawkesworth
                        edited this journal and authored much of the contents. </note> or the
                    sublime imagery of <title><hi rendition="#italics"
                            >Carazan</hi></title>.<note><title>"Carazan's Dream, an Eastern
                            Story"</title> appeared in the <title><hi rendition="#italics"
                                >Adventurer</hi></title> No. 132 (Saturday, February 9,
                        1754).</note> In extended compositions of this kind, we miss the captivating
                    richness and wildness of the genuine Eastern tales; and the desire to elicit a
                    moral is commonly too apparent. The style also, which is generally adopted in
                    these tales, inclines to the turgid, and is apt to become tiresome in a
                    narrative of any length. <title><hi rendition="#italics"
                            >Vathek</hi></title><note><ref target="people.html#BeckfordWilliam"
                            >William Beckford</ref> first published this novel in Switzerland in
                        1787.</note>is the only modern composition which has seized the genuine
                    spirit of the Arabian tales: there is indeed in that fiction so much of the
                    fancy peculiar to the East, that it is difficult to imagine it has not had some
                    genuine tale of that origin for its basis.</p>
                <p><title><hi rendition="#italics">Almoran and Hamet</hi></title> may,
                    notwithstanding, be read with a degree of pleasure, especially by<lb/><fw
                        type="vol"><hi rendition="#smcaps">vol. xxvi.</hi></fw><fw type="sig"
                        >b</fw><pb n="ii"/>youth, to whom the allegorical mode of writing is
                    generally more agreeable than it is to those of more advanced life. The design
                    is to show that no outward circumstances, even such as may be produced by
                    changing the course of nature, are sufficient to procure happiness, if the mind
                    is not fitted for it by virtuous dispositions. There is merit in the idea of
                    making Almoran, under the form of Hamet, incapable of taking advantage of his
                    transformation in securing the affections of his mistress, which become
                    immediately alienated from that beloved form, when she finds the mind of her
                    supposed lover no longer the same. She despises Almoran under the form of Hamet,
                    and transfers her love to the real Hamet, believing him to be Almoran: but much
                    more might have been made of the frame of the story than is made of it.</p>
                <p><ref target="people.html#HawkesworthJohn">Dr. Hawkesworth</ref>'s genius was not
                    of the first order; but it was elegant, pleasing, and remarkably adapted to
                    those purposes of moral instruction and innocent entertainment to which he
                    uniformly devoted it.</p>
            </div>
